===Prelude===
{{Quote|My honored guests, be welcome within my walls and at my table. I extend to you my hospitality and protection in the light of the Seven.|Lord Walder to King Robb and his entourage|The Rains of Castamere (episode)}}
King Robb was lulled into a sense of security by Walder Frey because he had extended [[guest right]] to the Starks - formally eating salt and bread from the same bowl as his guests. To break guest right is to break all the laws of gods and men, thus while Robb and Catelyn were always wary of Walder Frey's intentions, they never thought that even such a despicable man as he would sink so low as to break such a sacred pact.

The betrayal was scheduled to occur after the formal ceremony and the bedding, with Edmure and Roslin safely away in another part of the castle to consummate their marriage.

The door of the great hall is closed and barred by Black Walder. Meanwhile, Roose Bolton and his men were to position themselves around the hall, secretly armed and armored. The signal for massacre to begin was for the musicians to play an instrumental version of &quot;[[The Rains of Castamere (song)|The Rains of Castamere]]&quot;.

===The Massacre===
{{Quote|Your Grace, I feel I've been remiss in my duties. I've given you meat and wine and music, but I havenâ&euro;&trade;t shown you the hospitality you deserve. My King has married and I owe my new Queen a wedding gift.|Lord Walder signals for the massacre to begin.|The Rains of Castamere (episode)}}
[[File:Talisa Stabbed.jpg|thumb|200px|Talisa is stabbed by Lame Lothar.]]
WalderÂ Frey eventually holds a hand up to cue the musicians to cease playing, addressing Robb and claiming that he has been negligent in his duties as a host by failing to present his king with a proper wedding gift. At this moment,Â RooseÂ Bolton gives Catelyn a knowing look and glances towards his left arm, prompting her to lift up his sleeve and reveal theÂ chain mailÂ he is wearing underneath.Â RooseÂ smiles ominously andÂ CatelynÂ realizes that they have been led into a trap: she slapsÂ RooseÂ across the face and then shouts to warn Robb, but it is too late.

At Walder Frey's signal, [[Lothar Frey]] approaches [[Talisa Stark]] from behind and begins to repeatedly stab her in the stomach with a dagger, killing her unborn child instantly and causing her to quickly succumb to her wounds. As this is occurring, the musicians hired for the wedding reveal themselves to beÂ a group of [[Assassin|assassins]],Â brandishing crossbows and firing on Robb Stark and the Northern leadership gathered in the main hall. After the first volley the Northern guests are attacked in the main hall by armed Frey and Bolton men, as the crossbowmen continue to pick off survivors. Some of the Northerners killed by the Freys fall dead into their own meals, which the same Frey men had set there earlier as their guests.Â 
[[File:Roose kills Robb S3 Ep9.jpg|150px|thumb|Roose Bolton murders Robb Stark.]]
Outside of the keep,Â Frey and Bolton men turn on the other Northern soldiers in the camps who had been heavily drinking during the celebrations, taking them completely by surprise.Â Half a dozen Frey crossbowmen approach [[Grey Wind]],Â Robb'sÂ [[Direwolves|direwolf]],Â who has been forbidden from entering the castle to prevent him from defending Robb during the massacre, and fatally shoot him with crossbows dead while he is trapped inside a pen.

Robb, while wounded with several crossbow bolts, crawls towards TalisaÂ and embraces her, devastated over the loss of his wife and unborn child.Â Lord Walder, seeing that Robb has survived the initial onslaught, raises a hand to halt the carnage and watches Robb's suffering with cruel amusement.Â Catelyn, who had taken refuge under her table, notices thatÂ Walder Frey'sÂ eighth wife,Â [[Joyeuse Erenford]], is hiding beneath Walder's table and rushes forward, dragging her out and putting a table knife to her throat. She beseeches Walder Frey to end the slaughter and allow Robb to leave.Â SheÂ offers herself as a hostage in exchange for Robb's life, desperately screaming at Robb to walk out while he can. When Robb fails to respond, she turns back to Walder andÂ promisesÂ that they will not retaliate if he is allowed to live. Walder fires back that she already swore an oath to him that Robb would marry his daughter, finally revealing his motive for the betrayal.Â In a last plea of desperation, she swears on her honor as a Tully and a Stark that if Robb is not allowed to walk out, she will slit Joyeuse's throat. Walder appears to consider her offer for a moment, before glibly responding that he'll simply &quot;find another.&quot;

Robb then somehow finds the strength to drag himself back onto his feet, and weakly calls out &quot;mother!&quot; to her in a daze. As CatelynÂ looks into Robb's eyes,Â Roose Bolton steps in front of Robb and tells him that &quot;the Lannisters send their regards,&quot; stabbing him through the heart. 
[[File:Catelyn_dies.jpg|thumb|200px|Catelyn is killed by &quot;Black&quot; Walder Rivers.]]
True to her word, Catelyn slits Joyeuse's throat and lets out a wail of grief, believing all of her sons to be dead.Â Catelyn then becomes catatonic, silently staring at Robb's corpse in shock and utter despair, not reacting as her own throat is slit nearly to the bone from behind by [[Walder Rivers|Black Walder Rivers]].&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Rains of Castamere (episode)]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;
[[File:Robb_Wind.png|thumb|300px|&quot;King in the North! King in the North!  Here comes the King in the North!&quot;]]
Afterward, as the massacre of the Stark army encamped outside the Twins rages on, the Freys horrifically desecrate Robb's corpse by decapitating it and sewing the head of his direwolf Grey Wind in its place, then parade it around the keep atop a horse; a final insult against the [[King in the North]].&lt;ref name=&quot;Mhysa&quot;&gt;&quot;[[Mhysa]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

Catelyn'sÂ corpse was also desecrated: in cruel mockery of traditional [[House Tully]] funeral customs, which involve cremating a body on a burning boat set adrift in the [[Trident|Trident River]], the Freys unceremoniously flung Lady Catelyn's corpse from the battlements of the Twins, throwing it into the river to rot as if it was trash.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[Two Swords]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

===Aftermath===
{{Quote|The Red Wedding they're calling it.  Walder Frey committed sacrilege that day.  He shared bread and salt with the Starks.  He offered them [[Guest right|guest right]]. The gods will have their vengeance...Frey will burn in the seventh hell for what he did.|A [[Farmer|Riverlands farmer]] loyal to the Tullys.|Breaker of Chains}}

The events of the Red Wedding effectivelyÂ end the conflict between House Stark and HouseÂ LannisterÂ in a decisive victory for KingÂ â&euro;&lsaquo;[[Joffrey Baratheon]]Â and HouseÂ Lannister.Â Not only was Robb Stark himself killed in the betrayal, but the entire Northern army that Robb Stark led to southern Westeros was also destroyed - save only for those forces of [[House Karstark]] which had earlier abandoned Robb to return home, and the forces of [[House Bolton]]Â which turned on the other Northern Houses. For his part in the betrayal, Lord Frey was granted the castle of Riverrun and promised Lannister protection from any northern retaliation.Â LordÂ WalderÂ had his men captureÂ [[Edmure Tully]] out of his marriage bed alive, asÂ [[Riverrun]]Â has not yet fallen toÂ LannisterÂ forces and LordÂ EdmureÂ is a valuable hostage to hopefully negotiate its surrender in the near future.Â RooseÂ Bolton, for his part in the Red Wedding, is awarded the title ofÂ [[Warden of the North]], drastically elevating his House's stature.&lt;ref name=&quot;Mhysa&quot;/&gt; The Boltons are also granted the lands of [[Winterfell]] itself.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Children]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt; 

Surviving Stark Bannermen also suffered from the loss; [[House Forrester]] found themselves under the submission of [[House Whitehill]], their long-standing enemy and Bolton bannermen.&lt;ref&gt;[[Game of Thrones: A Telltale Games Series]]&lt;/ref&gt;

The [[War of the Five Kings]] continues, however, as [[Balon Greyjoy]] still fights for the Iron Islands' independence and to hold on to his conquest in the North, while [[Stannis Baratheon]] continues to dispute [[Joffrey Baratheon]]'s right to the Iron Throne.

[[Brynden Tully|Bryndenâ&euro;&lsaquo; Tully]] had been present for the wedding but fortuitously, he had left the keep to relieve himself on a tree outside before the massacre in the main hall began. He then managed to fight his way out of the assault on the camps and slip away from the Twins during the confusion of the night-time ambush. Roose Bolton ruefully notes to Walder Frey the next day that he has escaped. Lord Walder is dismissive and says he won't get far, but Bolton is clearly concerned that the Blackfish will manage to reach the safety of Riverrun before he can be found.&lt;ref name=&quot;Mhysa&quot;/&gt;

[[Greatjon Umber]], one of the most powerful and loyal bannermen of House Stark, is not present at [[the Twins]] for the wedding, making him one of the few bannermen of House Stark that remains alive and free.&lt;ref&gt;[https://twitter.com/b_cogman/status/446300694090637312]&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[https://twitter.com/b_cogman/status/446329941031124992]&lt;/ref&gt;
